%I A394820 #12 Apr 08 2026 23:25:30
%S A394820 1,1,1,4,37,1031,85458,15181668,4555719925
%N A394820 Number of unlabeled minimally 4-rigid graphs on n vertices.
%C A394820 A graph G is (minimally) d-rigid, if every generic realization p in dimension d yields a framework (G,p) that is infinitesimally d-rigid; i.e., all its infinitesimal flexes are trivial.
%C A394820 Every minimally 4-rigid graph with n>4 is (4,10)-sparse, that is every subgraph with n'>=4 vertices spans at most 4n'-10 edges. Minimally 4-rigid graphs have 4n-10 edges and hence are (4,10)-tight but not every (4,10)-tight graph is minimally 4-rigid.
%D A394820 Walter Whiteley, Some matroids from discrete applied geometry, in Matroid Theory, Contemporary Mathematics, 197, 1996.
%H A394820 Matteo Gallet, Georg Grasegger, Matthias Himmelmann and Jan Legerský, <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2505.22652">PyRigi -- a general-purpose Python package for the rigidity and flexibility of bar-and-joint frameworks</a>, arXiv:2505.22652 [math.MG], 2025.
%H A394820 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18548603">Dataset of minimally d-rigid graphs</a>, 2026.
%H A394820 Georg Grasegger, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.7457820">RigiComp - A Mathematica package for computational rigidity of graphs</a>, 2022.
%H A394820 PyRigi Developers, <a href="https://pyrigi.github.io/PyRigi/math/rigidity.html">Rigidity Theory</a>, 2025.
%e A394820 The complete graphs on four and five vertices are minimally 4-rigid. So is the complete graph on six vertices with one edge removed. The three graphs that can be obtained from the previous one by adding a new vertex and connecting it to 4 of the existing vertices, are also minimally 4-rigid.
%Y A394820 Cf. A227117, A328419.
%K A394820 nonn,more
%O A394820 4,4
